A push is when you actively reach out to customers to get them to use your product, while a pull is when customers come to you on their own, often through word of mouth or other organic means.
In the context of Jobs-to-be-Done (JTBD), a "push" refers to a situation where a company actively promotes a product or service to potential customers, often through marketing and advertising efforts. The company is essentially "pushing" the product onto the market and trying to convince people to buy it.

On the other hand, a "pull" occurs when customers actively seek out a product or service because they have a specific job they need to get done, and they believe that the product or service will help them accomplish that job. In this case, the customer's need or desire for the product "pulls" them towards it, rather than the company pushing it onto them.

To create an LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor with Arduino, you can follow these steps:

1. Connect the LM35 temperature sensor to your Arduino board. The sensor's VCC and GND pins should be connected to the Arduino's power and ground, respectively. The analog output pin of the LM35 should be connected to the Arduino's analog input pin A0 [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

2. Connect the LCD to the Arduino. If using an I2C LCD, you'll need to install the LiquidCrystal_I2C library in Arduino IDE. Go to Tools > Manage Libraries, search for "LiquidCrystal I2C" by Frank de Brabander, and click Install [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)].

3. Connect a 10K Ohm potentiometer to control the LCD's brightness. The potentiometer's first pin should be connected to VCC, the second pin to the LCD's pin 3, and the third pin to GND [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

4. Upload the code to your Arduino board. You can find sample code in the provided web search results [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd), [2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd), [3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)]. To enable C++20 in Visual Studio:

1. Right-click on your project in the Solution Explorer
2. Select "Properties"
3. Go to "Configuration Properties" > "C/C++" > "Language"
4. Set "C++ Language Standard" to "ISO C++20 Standard (/std:c++20)"
5. Click "Apply" and then "OK"
